00:04:56.630 --> 00:05:00.020
a DC based trio of dynamic women.

00:05:00.020 --> 00:05:04.280
So, I am going to just start
a little bit, oh my gosh,

00:05:04.280 --> 00:05:10.100
with the origins of women's
music and what I have

00:05:10.100 --> 00:05:13.170
out on the table is
pretty self-explanatory,

00:05:13.170 --> 00:05:14.920
but I will explain anyway.

00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:17.120
Ah, we really begin with drumming.

00:05:17.120 --> 00:05:20.800
Drumming is one of the
most ancient of the ways

00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:25.710
that women created sound, very much
like the heartbeat and the baby

00:05:25.710 --> 00:05:30.920
that lies in the womb, but
also often off limits to women

00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:36.540
who were not permitted to
join male only rituals,

00:05:36.540 --> 00:05:38.720
celebrations, and drum training.

00:05:38.720 --> 00:05:42.580
And that remains a very
frustrating issue for many women

00:05:42.580 --> 00:05:47.400
in different tribes globally
from the South Pacific to Africa.

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:52.600
And in the spaces around
band instrumental training,

00:05:52.600 --> 00:05:57.110
we find women turning to the
obvious lullabies and passing along

00:05:57.110 --> 00:06:01.870
to their babies both soothing
sounds and whispered information,

00:06:01.870 --> 00:06:06.960
whispered information you know
that was often in a secret language

00:06:06.960 --> 00:06:11.230
where women even were not permitted
the regular language of the men.

00:06:11.230 --> 00:06:15.610
That was very true in my personal
heritage, Jewish tradition

00:06:15.610 --> 00:06:19.500
where in Eastern Europe men
spoke of serious things in Hebrew

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:22.590
and women said rude things
about guys in Yiddish.

00:06:22.590 --> 00:06:28.930 position:56%
And the Yiddish lullabies are filled
with despair about the unreliability

00:06:28.930 --> 00:06:33.750
of men and that was considered a
women's language or the mamalotion,

00:06:33.750 --> 00:06:37.350
and I will give you a little
sample of that in a minute.

00:06:37.350 --> 00:06:41.150
By the time we get
to the Middle Ages,

00:06:41.150 --> 00:06:43.500
what we have is a curious issue

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:48.300
where women are composing sacred
music and it's very beautiful.

00:06:48.300 --> 00:06:53.020
As nuns, they can go to
a convent or a sisterhood

00:06:53.020 --> 00:06:54.970
of living, different kinds.

00:06:54.970 --> 00:06:57.520
The baekings are a
different kind of convent.

00:06:57.520 --> 00:07:00.870
They were allowed to own
property and eventually leave.

00:07:00.870 --> 00:07:04.690
But all of these women were
forbidden to sing in front of men

00:07:04.690 --> 00:07:08.160
and by really pretty early
in history there's a ban

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:12.210
on men listening to
women's voices with the idea

00:07:12.210 --> 00:07:17.250
that it could turn them, arouse
them, you know, what have you.

00:07:20.430 --> 00:07:23.940
One of the few contemporary
artifacts about this,

00:07:23.940 --> 00:07:28.290
this is from a Hasidic community
that I studied in grad school,

00:07:28.290 --> 00:07:31.180
Rabbinic Advisory, Woman Singing.

00:07:31.180 --> 00:07:34.930
Okay, so this would be on an
album warning young religious men,

00:07:34.930 --> 00:07:37.920
don't buy this album, there
are women on it, you know.

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:44.970
Okay, yeah I know, so we have
let's say compositions by someone

00:07:44.970 --> 00:07:47.150
like Hildegard of Bingen.

00:07:47.150 --> 00:07:55.080
And her recordings are available
to us now, if I can find them.

00:07:55.080 --> 00:07:57.730
Ah, here we go.

00:07:57.730 --> 00:08:01.990
And this is a, she's obviously
not really available to us

00:08:01.990 --> 00:08:07.500
at you know DAR Constitution Hall
right now, but she's reminded,

00:08:07.500 --> 00:08:12.290
ah we have access to her
recordings through compilations.

00:08:12.290 --> 00:08:17.560 position:56%
This is called Joan of Arc and it is
all music that was dedicated to Mary

00:08:17.560 --> 00:08:22.180 position:56%
from the Middle Ages and it includes
some of Hildegard's compositions

00:08:22.180 --> 00:08:26.290
and other songs about the
hardship of being a female.

00:08:26.290 --> 00:08:32.220
By the time we get to the Middle
Ages and a little bit after,

00:08:32.220 --> 00:08:36.890
we also have well-known songs
that are passed woman to woman

00:08:36.890 --> 00:08:43.020
that are very much about the
trauma of an unplanned pregnancy.

00:08:43.020 --> 00:08:46.750
So many women were burned as
witches, so many women were charged

00:08:46.750 --> 00:08:51.660
with deviant, sinful behavior
and burned at the stake.

00:08:51.660 --> 00:08:57.590 position:56%
And one of my colleagues and
friends in grad school, Deb Symonds,

00:08:57.590 --> 00:09:01.180
did her dissertation
on Scotts Ballads

00:09:01.180 --> 00:09:05.090
about illegitimate
birth and infanticide.

00:09:05.090 --> 00:09:09.120
And that is the book on the table
that's called "Weep Not for Me."

00:09:09.120 --> 00:09:14.870 position:56%
Those songs were very much trickling
down into contemporary folk tunes

00:09:14.870 --> 00:09:19.550 position:56%
and that's something that's familiar
to many of you from Mary Hamilton.

00:09:19.550 --> 00:09:24.380
Mary Hamilton's Birth the
Babe and the queen says,

00:09:24.380 --> 00:09:28.070
"Get up Mary Hamilton, get
up and follow me for I'm gone

00:09:28.070 --> 00:09:31.330
to Edinbro Town and
I'm gonna tell the King

00:09:31.330 --> 00:09:33.370
and Queen about your situation."

00:09:33.370 --> 00:09:37.080
That is all over England and
Ireland so it's indication

00:09:37.080 --> 00:09:40.280
that women were singing about
their situations to each other.

00:09:40.280 --> 00:09:44.040
It was just rarely written down and
it was a warning to younger women.

00:09:44.040 --> 00:09:47.440
So we have you know sort of
proto feminist music that's

00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:51.850
about the reality of the body and
the reality of living conditions,

00:09:51.850 --> 00:09:54.240
in particular, all over the world.

00:09:54.240 --> 00:09:58.520 position:56%
Where there is constant warfare,
there are absent men that women pine

00:09:58.520 --> 00:10:01.920
for and then there are
men who come in and invade

00:10:01.920 --> 00:10:03.730
and they invade physically.

00:10:03.730 --> 00:10:07.110
And those realities
are captured in song.

00:10:07.110 --> 00:10:10.010
And obviously in the
American version,

00:10:10.010 --> 00:10:17.120
what we have in the early
America are slave songs and songs

00:10:17.120 --> 00:10:19.850 position:56%
of survival and struggle and escape.

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:24.840
And the people who have studied
slave songs and work songs

00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:28.440
of course have done
enormous, meticulous research

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:32.670
on what was the music
that was actually a map

00:10:32.670 --> 00:10:36.300
to the underground
railroad and how to navigate

00:10:36.300 --> 00:10:38.310
to freedom by looking at the stars.

00:10:38.310 --> 00:10:42.090
And the most famous example there
is, follow the drinking gourd,

00:10:42.090 --> 00:10:43.830 position:56%
and of course that's the Big Dipper.

00:10:43.830 --> 00:10:46.840
I always get chills when
I write, speak about that.

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:50.380
That's such an important
piece of our musical history.

00:10:50.380 --> 00:10:55.930
So by the time we get to
the Era of Immigration,

00:10:55.930 --> 00:11:00.770
we start to get scratchy
recorded music, a little bit,

00:11:00.770 --> 00:11:07.370
and there's one group, Libana
that has done a sort of recreation

00:11:07.370 --> 00:11:12.850
of sweatshop songs by women
more than a hundred years ago

00:11:12.850 --> 00:11:16.490
and these are in Yiddish and
I'll just play you a tiny sample.

00:11:16.490 --> 00:11:19.670 position:56%
A woman is singing I am so
exhausted, when am I going to sleep?

00:11:19.670 --> 00:11:20.970
This is never ending.

00:11:20.970 --> 00:11:24.220
I am always going to
be you know a tailor.

00:11:28.410 --> 00:11:53.030
[Music plays] Okay sorry I can't
do more than just a little bit.

00:11:53.030 --> 00:12:10.940
