00:12:20.450 --> 00:12:25.500
When we get to the era of
suffrage, we actually have

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:31.590
down in the other exhibit some
sheet music from suffrage songs

00:12:31.590 --> 00:12:33.370
which are just fantastic.

00:12:33.370 --> 00:12:37.880
And World War I is a great
time to study opinionated women

00:12:37.880 --> 00:12:41.130
because there were women who were
for the war, against the war,

00:12:41.130 --> 00:12:43.150
women who said I don't even
want to talk about the war.

00:12:43.150 --> 00:12:46.710
Let's get the vote first before
I lift a finger for Wilson.

00:12:46.710 --> 00:12:49.520
And one of my favorite songs
is Who Dares to Put a Musket

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:53.530
on His Shoulder which was a women's
complaint that without the vote

00:12:53.530 --> 00:12:58.310
or any political input, she was
having to sacrifice her sons.

00:12:58.310 --> 00:13:01.630
Mothers were very hostile
to the Great War

00:13:01.630 --> 00:13:06.430
because it introduced three
horrifying new weapons of warfare.

00:13:06.430 --> 00:13:09.330
No one had ever seen
before the machine gun,

00:13:09.330 --> 00:13:12.540
mustard gas which was the
beginning of chemical warfare,

00:13:12.540 --> 00:13:15.920
and then the U boat, the
undersea boat that could

00:13:15.920 --> 00:13:21.140
of course sink pleasure
ships like the Lusitania.

00:13:21.140 --> 00:13:25.840
And so suffrage songs are the first
sort of recorded feminist music

00:13:25.840 --> 00:13:28.810
in terms of how we
see the first wave

00:13:28.810 --> 00:13:31.010
and the second wave, and so forth.

00:13:31.010 --> 00:13:35.930
But a lot of that is specific
to a kind of community

00:13:35.930 --> 00:13:38.390
of activists of white women.

00:13:38.390 --> 00:13:42.720
Over here we also have
eventually the Harlem Renaissance

00:13:42.720 --> 00:13:47.850
which is going to record
very outspoken Blues

00:13:49.170 --> 00:13:53.230
and living outside the
law, songs of survival

00:13:53.230 --> 00:13:58.210
from African American women, a lot
of gay women, and people meeting

00:13:58.210 --> 00:14:01.110
in speakeasies where
they could speak easy.

00:14:01.110 --> 00:14:04.550
So the interesting thing about
prohibition is it brought black

00:14:04.550 --> 00:14:05.970
and white, straight
and gay together.

00:14:05.970 --> 00:14:08.710
Because everyone was a criminal
as soon as you wanted to drink,

00:14:08.710 --> 00:14:10.920
and that was a great equalizer.

00:14:10.920 --> 00:14:16.110
So one of the most marvelous
things that I found is an example

00:14:16.110 --> 00:14:22.770 position:56%
of a party mix tape that someone put
together and I bought from a catalog

00:14:22.770 --> 00:14:25.850
when I was fifteen and
it's called Reefer Songs.

00:14:25.850 --> 00:14:32.750
Trixie Smith saying I'm so high.

00:14:32.750 --> 00:14:35.320
A little contrast to
Yiddish suffering,

00:14:35.320 --> 00:14:36.750
if we could just get
them together, you know.

00:14:36.750 --> 00:14:40.090
[Music plays] I'm so high,
I'm so high [Music plays].

00:14:40.090 --> 00:14:42.730
All right, kinda fun.

00:14:42.730 --> 00:14:52.720
This is from Smithsonian
