00:25:39.110 --> 00:25:44.950
of those vocalizations made it
possible for me to naturally

00:25:44.950 --> 00:25:49.360
to respond to women's music when
it sort of begins in the 70s.

00:25:49.360 --> 00:25:51.910
So, what do we call women's music?

00:25:51.910 --> 00:25:58.030
Women's music revives in the
early 70s as a kind of response

00:25:58.030 --> 00:26:01.490
to the belittlement of
women in rock and roll

00:26:01.490 --> 00:26:05.410
where many women were treated
as groupies, as sex objects,

00:26:05.410 --> 00:26:10.800
there were a lot of otherwise, you
know, radical and hip male bands

00:26:10.800 --> 00:26:14.120
that sang about women in
sexually demeaning ways.

00:26:14.120 --> 00:26:18.540
A really good example, the beloved
Rolling Stones, Under My Thumb,

00:26:18.540 --> 00:26:19.870
yes there is a problem with that.

00:26:19.870 --> 00:26:24.300
And even my beloved, beloved
Led Zepplin, way down inside,

00:26:24.300 --> 00:26:25.920
I'm going to give you
every inch of my love.

00:26:25.920 --> 00:26:27.260
Really? Okay.

00:26:27.260 --> 00:26:33.970
So anyhow, the response to that was
that women began to compose songs

00:26:33.970 --> 00:26:37.400 position:56%
about their lives that were original

00:26:37.400 --> 00:26:40.430
and that investigated
the issues of the day.

00:26:40.430 --> 00:26:44.490
And one of the first
was Mountain Moving Day

00:26:44.490 --> 00:26:46.050
and that album is out there.

00:26:46.050 --> 00:26:51.240
That was 1972 and that
was the New Haven

00:26:51.240 --> 00:26:55.180
and Chicago Women's
Liberation Rock Bands.

00:26:55.180 --> 00:27:00.060
And those are a combination of
songs about sexual harassment,

00:27:00.060 --> 00:27:04.980
contraception, abuse in the
home, talking back to patriarchy.

00:27:04.980 --> 00:27:06.450
It's just thrilling.

00:27:06.450 --> 00:27:10.130
And the title is symbolic,
the mountain is awake

00:27:10.130 --> 00:27:12.380
and women are on the move.

00:27:12.380 --> 00:27:18.670
That followed a commercially
successful all women's band, Fanny,

00:27:18.670 --> 00:27:22.110
with June Millington who now owns
a rock and roll camp for girls

00:27:22.110 --> 00:27:25.290
in Massachusetts, as a top 40 hit.

00:27:25.290 --> 00:27:29.790
But the feminist music
begins in '72,

00:27:29.790 --> 00:27:33.930
and then in '73 we get Olivia
Records and that is the great,

00:27:33.930 --> 00:27:39.800
great story that has
brought me into activism.

00:27:39.800 --> 00:27:43.510
The story of Olivia is that
a collective of women living

00:27:43.510 --> 00:27:45.700
in the Furies House here in DC

00:27:45.700 --> 00:27:51.790 position:56%
who were radical lesbian separatists
interviewed a visiting performer,

00:27:51.790 --> 00:27:57.460
Cris Williamson on Georgetown's
Radio Free Woman Program.

00:27:57.460 --> 00:28:02.310 position:56%
And during that interview, Cris
Williamson sort of turned the tables

00:28:02.310 --> 00:28:06.100
on the woman interviewing
her and said what do you do?

00:28:06.100 --> 00:28:09.450
And the Furies said
everything we do is about women.

00:28:09.450 --> 00:28:12.960
We create institutions, we want
women to be able to do things

00:28:12.960 --> 00:28:16.190
on their own without relying
on men, and on the air,

00:28:16.190 --> 00:28:19.780
Cris said why don't you start
a women's recording company?

00:28:19.780 --> 00:28:21.190
And they did the next day.

00:28:21.190 --> 00:28:26.620
So that was Olivia Records
which was the beginning

00:28:26.620 --> 00:28:28.790 position:56%
of a woman-owned production company.

00:28:28.790 --> 00:28:34.370 position:56%
It is now Olivia Travel and Olivia
Cruises where I often guest lecture.

00:28:34.370 --> 00:28:38.860
And that was very much under
the leadership of Judy Dlugacz

00:28:38.860 --> 00:28:43.600
who is still the head of Olivia
and their interest was in trying

00:28:43.600 --> 00:28:48.390 position:56%
to have concerts for women only that
would be uplifting and supportive,

00:28:48.390 --> 00:28:53.260 position:56%
but also which would name the ways
that women were beginning to be open

00:28:53.260 --> 00:28:54.950
about loving one another.

00:28:54.950 --> 00:28:58.950
And it was a very dramatic change
from what existed at the time.

00:28:58.950 --> 00:29:03.070
You had to find women to do sound
and do lighting and production

00:29:03.070 --> 00:29:05.670
and all of those skills had
been off limits to women.

00:29:05.670 --> 00:29:11.670 position:56%
And eventually Boden Sandstrom Women
Sound Company which she cofounded

00:29:11.670 --> 00:29:14.240
with Casey Culver and
another woman began

00:29:14.240 --> 00:29:16.530
to do the sound for these events.

00:29:16.530 --> 00:29:20.100
And Olivia's first album,
well actually I have some

00:29:20.100 --> 00:29:22.740
of the original forty-five
singles there,

00:29:22.740 --> 00:29:25.590
it's the rarest thing on the bench.

00:29:25.590 --> 00:29:29.230
They recorded Meg Christian's,
I Know You Know,

00:29:29.230 --> 00:29:33.060
which is a really fantastic album.

00:29:33.060 --> 00:29:36.740
And it was followed by Cris
Williamson's, The Changer

00:29:36.740 --> 00:29:40.470
and the Changed, which to this day
is the best-selling women's music

00:29:40.470 --> 00:29:42.240
album of all time.

00:29:42.240 --> 00:29:46.070
This was great, but where are
these women going to perform?

00:29:46.070 --> 00:29:50.860
And who's going to review
them and distribute the music?

00:29:50.860 --> 00:29:53.170
There was no coverage
in the mainstream

00:29:53.170 --> 00:29:54.850
of this movement in the 70s.

00:29:54.850 --> 00:29:58.700
There was no real way to promote
it without putting women at risk

00:29:58.700 --> 00:30:02.250
as soon as it was identified
as something gay.

00:30:02.250 --> 00:30:07.440
You could lose your job, your
custody, your standing in church,

00:30:07.440 --> 00:30:11.210
your role in a school,
everything if you just showed

00:30:11.210 --> 00:30:13.460
up at a Holly Near concert.

00:30:13.460 --> 00:30:17.700
So a lot of this history
has a very slim paper trail

00:30:17.700 --> 00:30:20.560
which is very frustrating
to me as a historian.

00:30:20.560 --> 00:30:22.770
As things digitize, all

00:30:22.770 --> 00:30:25.800
that a researcher will find
is what has been digitized

00:30:25.800 --> 00:30:27.830
so far, not the complete story.

00:30:27.830 --> 00:30:31.820
And the complete story of these
recordings is women playing

00:30:31.820 --> 00:30:35.380
in other women's living
rooms with the shades drawn.

00:30:35.380 --> 00:30:37.150
And it's in women's scrapbooks.

00:30:37.150 --> 00:30:41.700
It's in photos, it's in
memories, it is in oral tradition

00:30:41.700 --> 00:30:43.230
which we have to get now.

00:30:43.230 --> 00:30:46.400
So I'm adamant about interviewing
women who went to concerts

00:30:46.400 --> 00:30:48.290
and their lives were changed.

00:30:48.290 --> 00:30:49.990 position:56%
And it didn't necessarily have to be

00:30:49.990 --> 00:30:52.500
about the intimacy
of a relationship.

00:30:52.500 --> 00:30:55.760
A lot of what women will
say "saved their lives" was

00:30:55.760 --> 00:30:59.720
